  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Law vs. Guidance in Practice",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between statutory laws and non-statutory guidance within a real-world electrical installation context.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Statutory regulations like the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR) are mandatory laws passed by Parliament.",
      "Non-statutory regulations like BS 7671 (The Wiring Regs) provide the technical standards and 'how-to' instructions.",
      "While only one is 'the law,' they work together to ensure an installation is safe and legally compliant."
    ],
    "questionText": "An apprentice suggests that because BS 7671 is 'non-statutory,' it isn't as important as the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR). Explain the relationship between these two documents and why an electrician must use BS 7671 to satisfy their legal duties under the EAWR.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Identify that the EAWR is a statutory regulation (the law) that sets out broad legal safety requirements.",
      "Identify that BS 7671 is a non-statutory regulation (guidance) that provides the specific technical details for safe installation.",
      "Explain that following the non-statutory guidance (BS 7671) is the industry-recognised way to prove that the statutory legal requirements (EAWR) have been met.",
      "Conclude that while BS 7671 isn't a law itself, failing to follow it makes it very difficult to prove you have complied with the EAWR in a court of law."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which one tells you 'what' you must achieve legally and which one tells you 'how' to actually wire it to reach that standard."
